PES_Bayesian — Pandemic Emergency Scenario with Bayesian Optimisation

Variant of the PES experiment that adds Bayesian hyperparameter optimisation
(Optuna / TPE) on top of Q-Learning.  A pre-trained RL-Agent allocates limited
resources to cities to minimise disease spread; the Bayesian search finds the
hyperparameters that maximise normalised performance over the 64 evaluation sequences.

## Key Features:
- Bayesian optimisation of Q-Learning hyperparameters (Optuna, TPE sampler)
- Resumable optimisation via SQLite persistence (--resume YYYY-MM-DD)
- Best Q-table preserved in memory during search (no lossy re-training)
- Infeasible-action masking in evaluation (consistent with __main__.py)
- RL-Agent based decision-making (Q-Learning with ε-greedy)
- Single-agent architecture (no human interaction)
- Console-based output with ANSI colour formatting
- Training pipeline included (ext/train_rl.py) for standalone training

## RL-Agent Technical Specification:
- **State space**: (resources_left, city_number, severity)
  - Resources: 0-30 values
  - City/Trial number: 0-12 values
  - Severity: 0-10 values
- **Action space**: Resource allocation (0-10, discrete)
- **Training**: up to 1,000,000 episodes using Q-Learning algorithm
- **Q-Table dimensions**: 31 × 13 × 11 × 11 (after reshaping)
- **Policy**: Greedy (deterministic) with epsilon-decay during training
- **Confidence estimation**: Entropy-based metacognitive scores
- **Training seed**: CONFIG.SEED (default 42) — reproducible across runs

## Bayesian Optimisation — Search Space:
| Parameter        | Range               | Scale       |
|------------------|---------------------|-------------|
| learning_rate    | [0.10, 0.4]         | logarithmic |
| discount_factor  | [0.80, 0.99]        | linear      |
| epsilon_initial  | [0.40, 1.0]         | linear      |
| epsilon_min      | [0.05, 0.10]        | linear      |
| num_episodes     | [800 000, 1 000 000]| step 100 000|

## Experiment Structure:
- Total Experiment: 1
- Blocks: 8
- Sequences per Block: 8 (64 total sequences)
- Trials per Sequence: 3-10 (approximately 360 total trials)
- Decision per Trial: Resource allocation to a single city

## Core Modules:
- **PES_Bayesian/__main__.py**: Experiment execution loop (RL-Agent)
- **PES_Bayesian/ext/optimize_rl.py**: Bayesian optimisation pipeline
- **PES_Bayesian/ext/train_rl.py**: Standalone RL-Agent training
- **PES_Bayesian/ext/pandemic.py**: Gym environment and Q-Learning algorithm
- **PES_Bayesian/src/exp_utils.py**: Severity calculations and aggregation
- **PES_Bayesian/src/log_utils.py**: Dual-stream logging (console + file)
- **PES_Bayesian/src/pygameMediator.py**: RL-Agent response generation with entropy-based confidence
- **PES_Bayesian/src/result_formatter.py**: Report generation and visualisation
- **PES_Bayesian/src/terminal_utils.py**: ANSI colour formatting utilities
- **PES_Bayesian/config/CONFIG.py**: Experiment configuration (incl. SEED)

## Files Generated (optimisation):
- q_best_<date>.npy: Best Q-Table from optimisation
- rewards_best_<date>.npy: Reward history of the best training run
- optimization_results_<date>.txt: Full report (all trials, best params)
- optimization_history_<date>.png: Convergence plot
- hyperparameter_importances_<date>.png: Parameter importance (fANOVA)
- optuna_study_<date>.db: SQLite database (resumable)

## Files Generated (experiment):
- responses_*.txt: Agent decisions and confidence scores
- info_*.txt: Experiment metadata and configuration
- log_*.txt: Detailed execution logs

## Usage:
- Execute experiment:       python3 -m PES_Bayesian
- Train new RL-Agent:       python3 -m PES_Bayesian.ext.train_rl
- Run Bayesian optimisation: python3 -m PES_Bayesian.ext.optimize_rl [n_trials] [--resume YYYY-MM-DD]

## Documentation:
- **bayesian_optimization_guide.md**: Practical guide — launch, resume, logs
- **optimize_rl_explained.md**: Theory ↔ code mapping of the optimisation pipeline

## Configuration:
Flexible configuration via config/CONFIG.py with parameters for:
- Player type selection (RL-Agent)
- Resource availability and severity bounds
- Block/sequence/trial structure (8×8×3-10)
- Reproducibility (SEED = 42 for Q-Learning training)
- Output preferences and verbosity levels

